        {
          "feedback": "Contar folhas pode ser interessante em outro objetivo, mas não resolve a principal lacuna do registro.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Número de folhas ao redor"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "format": "selectImage",
      "question": "Qual desenho de campo seria mais útil para estudar a estrutura de um pequeno crustáceo visto na praia?",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Capricho artístico não substitui informação estrutural. Faltam rótulos e partes comparáveis.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "prompt": "Desenho sombreado e detalhista, bonito, mas sem nomes das partes e sem indicar a vista"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Esse funciona bem como ferramenta científica: mostra proporções, partes relevantes e a vista observada.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "prompt": "Desenho simples do animal em vista superior, com patas, carapaça e antenas rotuladas e proporções coerentes"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Expressa uma impressão geral, mas não ajuda muito a comparar estruturas.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "prompt": "Rabisco muito pequeno com corpo redondo sem patas visíveis nem marcação de partes"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Mistura mais de uma posição sem explicar qual foi observada, o que atrapalha a interpretação.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "prompt": "Desenho do animal com frente e lado sobrepostos no mesmo contorno, sem indicação de vista"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "format": "sortOrder",
      "question": "Coloque em ordem uma sequência sensata para registrar um organismo no campo sem perder contexto nem detalhes importantes.",
      "items": [
        "Anotar data, hora e local",
        "Observar o organismo no ambiente e registrar comportamento visível",
        "Fazer foto, vídeo ou áudio preservando o enquadramento e o arquivo original",
        "Completar a anotação com condições do momento e dúvidas",
        "Fazer um desenho simples com rótulos das estruturas relevantes"
      ],
      "feedback": "Primeiro vem o contexto básico. Depois, a observação direta do organismo no ambiente. Em seguida, o registro de mídia preserva evidências. Então vale completar condições e dúvidas. Por fim, o desenho ajuda a notar e organizar estruturas que merecem atenção."
    },
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": "Uma pessoa filmou um lagarto por 4 segundos. O vídeo mostra o movimento da cauda, mas não deixa claro o padrão das escamas da cabeça. Ela também fez um desenho rotulado da cabeça no caderno.",
      "question": "Qual conclusão faz mais sentido?",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Nem tudo precisa sair de um único tipo de registro. Fontes diferentes podem se complementar bem.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "O desenho deve ser descartado"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Isso. O vídeo registra melhor o movimento, enquanto o desenho pode destacar estruturas específicas observadas com atenção.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Cada registro serve melhor a coisas diferentes"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Vídeo ajuda muito, mas não substitui toda anotação ou desenho em qualquer situação.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "O vídeo basta para qualquer análise"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Desenho sozinho também não resolve tudo, especialmente quando o comportamento importa.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Só o desenho é evidência válida"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}

{
  "questions": [
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": "A language-learning app wants to understand whether a redesigned onboarding flow helps new users reach their first real moment of value. The team is debating what the funnel should measure.",
      "question": "Which funnel is the best fit?",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Not quite. Creating an account is an early step, but it doesn't capture whether someone reached meaningful value in the product.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Ad click → account created → email verified"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Yes. This starts from a clear entry point and ends at a real user outcome that matches the question about onboarding success.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "App install → lesson started → first lesson completed"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Close, but this mixes broad marketing activity with a weak end point that may not reflect product value.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Website visit → pricing page viewed → push alerts enabled"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "This is too late in the journey for an onboarding question and skips the first-value milestone the team wants to understand.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Subscription started → profile edited → friend invited"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "format": "selectImage",
      "question": "You're checking whether a sudden conversion drop is likely caused by tracking trouble rather than behavior change. Which dashboard view would be the strongest clue?",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "This is the best clue. If one step collapses suddenly while neighboring steps look stable, broken instrumentation is a strong possibility.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "prompt": "A funnel chart where steps 1 and 2 are steady for weeks, but step 3 drops sharply to near zero on one specific day"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "This could reflect a real growth trend, not necessarily a measurement issue.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "prompt": "A line chart where every step in the funnel rises gradually over a month with small day-to-day variation"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "This suggests a stable difference between segments, which is not the same as a sudden tracking failure.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "prompt": "A bar chart comparing mobile and desktop conversion, with mobile consistently lower across all weeks"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "This might show seasonality or traffic swings, but it doesn't point as directly to a broken event.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "prompt": "A chart where all funnel steps dip together over a holiday weekend and recover afterward"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "format": "matchColumns",
      "pairs": [
        {
          "left": "A campaign brings many visitors, but few finish signup",
          "right": "Acquisition is high, conversion is weak"
        },
        {
          "left": "Users who joined last month still return weekly more than newer users",
          "right": "An older cohort has stronger retention"
        },
        {
          "left": "A metric moves before revenue changes and may help predict it",
          "right": "Leading indicator"
        },
        {
          "left": "People leave most heavily between step 2 and step 3",
          "right": "Dropoff is concentrated at one stage"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Match each product observation to the best analytics idea."
    },
    {
      "format": "fillBlank",
      "question": "Complete the statement so the team doesn't confuse symptoms with causes.",
      "template": "A metric that changes earlier and may help forecast an outcome is a [BLANK], while the business result that shows up later is a [BLANK].",
      "answers": [
        "leading indicator",
        "lagging indicator"
      ],
      "distractors": [
        "retention metric",
        "guardrail metric",
        "cohort",
        "dropoff"
      ],
      "feedback": "A leading indicator gives an earlier signal; a lagging indicator reflects the later outcome you ultimately care about. The key is that early signals can help prediction, but they aren't automatically the cause."
    },
    {
      "format": "sortOrder",
      "question": "Put these steps in the best order for diagnosing an unexpected funnel drop before proposing a product change.",
      "items": [
        "Confirm the event definitions and step ordering",
        "Check whether instrumentation changed or broke",
        "Review traffic mix, eligibility, bots, and seasonality",
        "Compare against a recent baseline and segment the change",
        "Decide whether a product action is warranted"
      ],
      "feedback": "Start by making sure the funnel itself is defined correctly. Then verify the data pipeline and event logging. After that, rule out mix and context changes, compare with a sensible baseline, and only then decide on a product response."
    },
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": "A grocery delivery team runs an A/B test on a shorter checkout. Checkout completion rises from 41.0% to 41.6%. However, customer support contacts per order also rise, and the result is statistically noisy with a very small expected revenue impact.",
      "question": "What's the best next move?",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Not yet. A tiny uplift with noisy evidence and a worse guardrail metric is not a strong case for full rollout.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Launch it to everyone because the primary metric went up"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "This overreacts. One mixed test result usually isn't enough reason to abandon the broader idea entirely.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Cancel all checkout work because the experiment failed"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Yes. This respects guardrails and practical significance instead of chasing a small, uncertain lift.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Investigate the support issue and refine the variant before another test"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Waiting for more time alone doesn't address the guardrail problem or improve the decision quality much.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Keep the test unchanged until the uplift becomes larger"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "format": "selectImage",
      "question": "A PM wants to compare retention fairly across signup months after a pricing change. Which visual setup is the best choice?",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Yes. A cohort retention view lets you compare groups that started at different times on the same lifecycle basis.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "prompt": "A table of signup-month cohorts with rows for each month and columns for week 1, week 2, week 3 retention percentages"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "This shows total active users over time, which mixes new and old users together and hides cohort behavior.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "prompt": "A single line chart of total weekly active users across the whole product for six months"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "This helps with traffic source comparison, but not with retention over time by starting group.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "prompt": "A pie chart showing the share of users from search, referrals, ads, and direct traffic"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "This focuses on one point in the funnel, not whether users keep coming back over later periods.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "prompt": "A funnel chart from landing page to signup completion for one recent week"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": "A meditation app sees trial-to-paid conversion fall this week. A PM wants to conclude that the new paywall caused it. Looking closer, paid social traffic doubled, many visitors were outside eligible countries, and the baseline week included a holiday promotion.",
      "question": "What's the strongest interpretation?",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Right. Several confounders changed at once, so the drop can't be pinned on the paywall yet.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "The evidence is mixed, so traffic and baseline effects should be checked first"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "This jumps too fast from correlation to cause without ruling out obvious data and mix changes.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "The paywall is clearly the cause because conversion fell after launch"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Segmentation helps, but saying channel never matters ignores a major source of funnel distortion.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Only country segmentation matters here; acquisition mix can be ignored"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "A single noisy week, especially around promotions, is not enough to declare the metric meaningless.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "The metric should be abandoned because weekly conversion is too unstable"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}

{
  "questions": [
